            {
              "id": "UnnecessaryFullyQualifiedName",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Unnecessary qualifier 'LayoutHelper': 'currentGroup' is already in scope because it is declared in an enclosing type"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "\nImport statements allow the use of non-fully qualified names.  The use of a fully qualified name\nwhich is covered by an import statement is redundant.  Consider using the non-fully qualified name.\n        "
              },
              "helpUri": "https://docs.pmd-code.org/snapshot/pmd_rules_java_codestyle.html#unnecessaryfullyqualifiedname",
              "help": {
                "text": "\nImport statements allow the use of non-fully qualified names.  The use of a fully qualified name\nwhich is covered by an import statement is redundant.  Consider using the non-fully qualified name.\n        "
              },
              "properties": {
                "ruleset": "Code Style",
                "priority": 4,
                "tags": [
                  "Code Style"
                ]
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "note"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "MethodArgumentCouldBeFinal",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Parameter 'newGroup' is not assigned and could be declared final"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "\n            Reports method and constructor parameters that can be made final because they are never reassigned within the body of the method.\n\n            This rule ignores unused parameters so as not to overlap with the rule {% rule java/bestpractices/UnusedFormalParameter %}.\n            It will also ignore the parameters of abstract methods.\n        "
              },
              "helpUri": "https://docs.pmd-code.org/snapshot/pmd_rules_java_codestyle.html#methodargumentcouldbefinal",
              "help": {
                "text": "\n            Reports method and constructor parameters that can be made final because they are never reassigned within the body of the method.\n\n            This rule ignores unused parameters so as not to overlap with the rule {% rule java/bestpractices/UnusedFormalParameter %}.\n            It will also ignore the parameters of abstract methods.\n        "
              },
              "properties": {
                "ruleset": "Code Style",
                "priority": 3,
                "tags": [
                  "Code Style"
                ]
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CognitiveComplexity",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The method 'doBracketedField(int)' has a cognitive complexity of 25, current threshold is 15"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "\n            Methods that are highly complex are difficult to read and more costly to maintain. If you include too much decisional\n            logic within a single method, you make its behavior hard to understand and more difficult to modify.\n\n            Cognitive complexity is a measure of how difficult it is for humans to read and understand a method. Code that contains\n            a break in the control flow is more complex, whereas the use of language shorthands doesn't increase the level of\n            complexity. Nested control flows can make a method more difficult to understand, with each additional nesting of the\n            control flow leading to an increase in cognitive complexity.\n\n            Information about Cognitive complexity can be found in the original paper here:\n            <https://www.sonarsource.com/docs/CognitiveComplexity.pdf>\n\n            By default, this rule reports methods with a complexity of 15 or more. Reported methods should be broken down into less\n            complex components.\n        "
              },
              "helpUri": "https://docs.pmd-code.org/snapshot/pmd_rules_java_design.html#cognitivecomplexity",
              "help": {
                "text": "\n            Methods that are highly complex are difficult to read and more costly to maintain. If you include too much decisional\n            logic within a single method, you make its behavior hard to understand and more difficult to modify.\n\n            Cognitive complexity is a measure of how difficult it is for humans to read and understand a method. Code that contains\n            a break in the control flow is more complex, whereas the use of language shorthands doesn't increase the level of\n            complexity. Nested control flows can make a method more difficult to understand, with each additional nesting of the\n            control flow leading to an increase in cognitive complexity.\n\n            Information about Cognitive complexity can be found in the original paper here:\n            <https://www.sonarsource.com/docs/CognitiveComplexity.pdf>\n\n            By default, this rule reports methods with a complexity of 15 or more. Reported methods should be broken down into less\n            complex components.\n        "
              },
              "properties": {
                "ruleset": "Design",
                "priority": 3,
                "tags": [
                  "Design"
                ]
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CyclomaticComplexity",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The method 'doBracketedField(int)' has a cyclomatic complexity of 11."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "\nThe complexity of methods directly affects maintenance costs and readability. Concentrating too much decisional logic\nin a single method makes its behaviour hard to read and change.\n\nCyclomatic complexity assesses the complexity of a method by counting the number of decision points in a method,\nplus one for the method entry. Decision points are places where the control flow jumps to another place in the\nprogram. As such, they include all control flow statements, such as `if`, `while`, `for`, and `case`. For more\ndetails on the calculation, see the documentation {% jdoc java::lang.java.metrics.JavaMetrics#CYCLO %}.\n\nGenerally, numbers ranging from 1-4 denote low complexity, 5-7 denote moderate complexity, 8-10 denote\nhigh complexity, and 11+ is very high complexity. By default, this rule reports methods with a complexity >= 10.\nAdditionally, classes with many methods of moderate complexity get reported as well once the total of their\nmethods' complexities reaches 80, even if none of the methods was directly reported.\n\nReported methods should be broken down into several smaller methods. Reported classes should probably be broken down\ninto subcomponents.\n        "
              },
              "helpUri": "https://docs.pmd-code.org/snapshot/pmd_rules_java_design.html#cyclomaticcomplexity",
              "help": {
                "text": "\nThe complexity of methods directly affects maintenance costs and readability. Concentrating too much decisional logic\nin a single method makes its behaviour hard to read and change.\n\nCyclomatic complexity assesses the complexity of a method by counting the number of decision points in a method,\nplus one for the method entry. Decision points are places where the control flow jumps to another place in the\nprogram. As such, they include all control flow statements, such as `if`, `while`, `for`, and `case`. For more\ndetails on the calculation, see the documentation {% jdoc java::lang.java.metrics.JavaMetrics#CYCLO %}.\n\nGenerally, numbers ranging from 1-4 denote low complexity, 5-7 denote moderate complexity, 8-10 denote\nhigh complexity, and 11+ is very high complexity. By default, this rule reports methods with a complexity >= 10.\nAdditionally, classes with many methods of moderate complexity get reported as well once the total of their\nmethods' complexities reaches 80, even if none of the methods was directly reported.\n\nReported methods should be broken down into several smaller methods. Reported classes should probably be broken down\ninto subcomponents.\n        "
              },
              "properties": {
                "ruleset": "Design",
                "priority": 3,
                "tags": [
                  "Design"
                ]
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "OnlyOneReturn",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "A method should have only one exit point, and that should be the last statement in the method"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "\nA method should have only one exit point, and that should be the last statement in the method.\n        "
              },
              "helpUri": "https://docs.pmd-code.org/snapshot/pmd_rules_java_codestyle.html#onlyonereturn",
              "help": {
                "text": "\nA method should have only one exit point, and that should be the last statement in the method.\n        "
              },
              "properties": {
                "ruleset": "Code Style",
                "priority": 3,
                "tags": [
                  "Code Style"
                ]
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "AvoidLiteralsInIfCondition",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Avoid using literals such as '}' in if statements"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "\nAvoid using hard-coded literals in conditional statements. By declaring them as static variables\nor private members with descriptive names maintainability is enhanced. By default, the literals \"-1\" and \"0\" are ignored.\nMore exceptions can be defined with the property \"ignoreMagicNumbers\".\n\nThe rule doesn't consider deeper expressions by default, but this can be enabled via the property `ignoreExpressions`.\nWith this property set to false, if-conditions like `i == 1 + 5` are reported as well. Note that in that case,\nthe property ignoreMagicNumbers is not taken into account, if there are multiple literals involved in such an expression.\n        "
              },
              "helpUri": "https://docs.pmd-code.org/snapshot/pmd_rules_java_errorprone.html#avoidliteralsinifcondition",
              "help": {
                "text": "\nAvoid using hard-coded literals in conditional statements. By declaring them as static variables\nor private members with descriptive names maintainability is enhanced. By default, the literals \"-1\" and \"0\" are ignored.\nMore exceptions can be defined with the property \"ignoreMagicNumbers\".\n\nThe rule doesn't consider deeper expressions by default, but this can be enabled via the property `ignoreExpressions`.\nWith this property set to false, if-conditions like `i == 1 + 5` are reported as well. Note that in that case,\nthe property ignoreMagicNumbers is not taken into account, if there are multiple literals involved in such an expression.\n        "
              },
              "properties": {
                "ruleset": "Error Prone",
                "priority": 3,
                "tags": [
                  "Error Prone"
                ]
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "AvoidDeeplyNestedIfStmts",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Deeply nested if..then statements are hard to read"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "\nAvoid creating deeply nested if-then statements since they are harder to read and error-prone to maintain.\n        "
              },
              "helpUri": "https://docs.pmd-code.org/snapshot/pmd_rules_java_design.html#avoiddeeplynestedifstmts",
              "help": {
                "text": "\nAvoid creating deeply nested if-then statements since they are harder to read and error-prone to maintain.\n        "
              },
              "properties": {
                "ruleset": "Design",
                "priority": 3,
                "tags": [
                  "Design"
                ]
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "AvoidInstantiatingObjectsInLoops",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Avoid instantiating new objects inside loops"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "\nNew objects created within loops should be checked to see if they can created outside them and reused.\n        "
              },
              "helpUri": "https://docs.pmd-code.org/snapshot/pmd_rules_java_performance.html#avoidinstantiatingobjectsinloops",
              "help": {
                "text": "\nNew objects created within loops should be checked to see if they can created outside them and reused.\n        "
              },
              "properties": {
                "ruleset": "Performance",
                "priority": 3,
                "tags": [
                  "Performance"
                ]
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CognitiveComplexity",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The method 'doBracketedOptionField()' has a cognitive complexity of 53, current threshold is 15"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "\n            Methods that are highly complex are difficult to read and more costly to maintain. If you include too much decisional\n            logic within a single method, you make its behavior hard to understand and more difficult to modify.\n\n            Cognitive complexity is a measure of how difficult it is for humans to read and understand a method. Code that contains\n            a break in the control flow is more complex, whereas the use of language shorthands doesn't increase the level of\n            complexity. Nested control flows can make a method more difficult to understand, with each additional nesting of the\n            control flow leading to an increase in cognitive complexity.\n\n            Information about Cognitive complexity can be found in the original paper here:\n            <https://www.sonarsource.com/docs/CognitiveComplexity.pdf>\n\n            By default, this rule reports methods with a complexity of 15 or more. Reported methods should be broken down into less\n            complex components.\n        "
              },
              "helpUri": "https://docs.pmd-code.org/snapshot/pmd_rules_java_design.html#cognitivecomplexity",
              "help": {
                "text": "\n            Methods that are highly complex are difficult to read and more costly to maintain. If you include too much decisional\n            logic within a single method, you make its behavior hard to understand and more difficult to modify.\n\n            Cognitive complexity is a measure of how difficult it is for humans to read and understand a method. Code that contains\n            a break in the control flow is more complex, whereas the use of language shorthands doesn't increase the level of\n            complexity. Nested control flows can make a method more difficult to understand, with each additional nesting of the\n            control flow leading to an increase in cognitive complexity.\n\n            Information about Cognitive complexity can be found in the original paper here:\n            <https://www.sonarsource.com/docs/CognitiveComplexity.pdf>\n\n            By default, this rule reports methods with a complexity of 15 or more. Reported methods should be broken down into less\n            complex components.\n        "
              },
